</emphasis>
currently comprises 22 species, including 19 new combinations transferred from 
<taxonomicName box="[212,310,621,644]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[212,310,621,644]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Panorpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and three new species, 
<taxonomicName box="[579,875,620,644]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Cerapanorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="liupanshana" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[579,875,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Cerapanorpa liupanshana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[881,970,620,645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[881,970,620,645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[1037,1130,620,645]" country="China" name="Ningxia" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Ningxia</collectingRegion>
, and 
<taxonomicName box="[1187,1341,620,644]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Cerapanorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="protrudens" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1187,1341,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">C. protrudens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1347,1436,620,645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1347,1436,620,645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[198,313,656,679]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Cerapanorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[198,313,656,679]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">C. sinuata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[320,410,655,680]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[320,410,655,680]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[478,572,655,680]" country="China" name="Shaanxi" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Shaanxi</collectingRegion>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,968]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
In the North American 
<taxonomicName box="[461,673,692,716]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufescens">
<emphasis box="[461,673,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Panorpa rufescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group, tergum VI of males is also produced posteriorly into a flat or conical projection, which is also called an anal horn (
<bibRefCitation author="Esben-Petersen" box="[848,1089,727,752]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" refString="Esben-Petersen, P. (1921) Mecoptera: Monographic Revision. Collections Zoologiques du Baron Edm. de Selys Longchamps. Catalogue Systematique et Descriptif, 5, 1 - 172." type="journal article" year="1921">Esben-Petersen 1921</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Carpenter" box="[1101,1278,728,752]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" refString="Carpenter, F. M. (1931) Revision of the Nearctic Mecoptera. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 72, 205 - 277." type="journal article" year="1931">Carpenter 1931</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Byers" box="[1291,1424,728,752]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" refString="Byers, G. W. (1993) Autumnal Mecoptera of southeastern United States. The University of Kansas Science Bulletin, 55, 57 - 96. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 773" type="journal article" year="1993">Byers 1993</bibRefCitation>
). However, the so-called anal horn of the 
<taxonomicName box="[594,727,764,788]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufescens">
<emphasis box="[594,727,764,788]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">P. rufescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group differs greatly from the digitate (finger-like) anal horn of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,302,800,823]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Cerapanorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,302,800,823]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Cerapanorpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[308,413,799,824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[308,413,799,824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in morphology.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,968]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
Based on our recent phylogenetic analysis of molecular data (
<bibRefCitation author="Hu" box="[887,1051,836,861]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" refString="Hu, G. L., Yan, G., Xu, H. &amp; Hua, B. Z. (2015) Molecular phylogeny of Panorpidae (Insecta: Mecoptera) based on mitochondrial and nuclear genes. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 85, 22 - 31. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2015.01.009" type="journal article" year="2015">
Hu 
<emphasis box="[929,985,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
), the species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1229,1380,836,859]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Cerapanorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1229,1380,836,859]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Cerapanorpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="3" pageNumber="96" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
constitute a well-supported clade, which diverges distantly from the North American species, indicating that the so-called anal horns are likely homoplasious characters between 
<taxonomicName box="[934,1085,908,931]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Cerapanorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[934,1085,908,931]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Cerapanorpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1093,1200,908,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1093,1200,908,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and the 
<taxonomicName box="[1301,1436,908,932]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufescens">
<emphasis box="[1301,1436,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">P. rufescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262941/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" targetBox="[188,1384,1042,1870]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1902,2017]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,280,1902,1924]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">FIGURE 2.</emphasis>
Female of 
<taxonomicName box="[411,626,1902,1924]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Cerapanorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obtusa">
<emphasis box="[411,626,1902,1924]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Cerapanorpa obtusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. (A) and (B) Abdominal segments VIII–XI, lateral and ventral views; (C) subgenital plate, ventral view; (D)–(F) genital plate, ventral, lateral and dorsal views (D from Ma 
<emphasis box="[1154,1200,1933,1955]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">et al</emphasis>
. 2014). Abbreviations: Ax, axis; DBP, dorsal basal plate; MP, main plate; PA, posterior arm; VBP, ventral basal plate. Scale bars: A, B, E = 0.20 mm, C = 0.10 mm, D, F = 0.25 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">
Species of 
<taxonomicName box="[329,480,152,175]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Cerapanorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[329,480,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">Cerapanorpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[491,599,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[491,599,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
usually inhabit elevated open areas in mountainous regions. The adults often occur in large populations, and some species may be especially abundant in dense 
<taxonomicName box="[1176,1285,188,211]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1176,1285,188,211]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">Artemisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1302,1428,188,212]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
) vegetation. The wings are held flat as a V-shape over the abdomen at rest (
<figureCitation box="[977,1039,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1537,1559]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,339,1492]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[188,1398,339,1512]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Cerapanorpa obtusa. (A) and (B) Male and female habitus, photo by Lu Jiang; (C) notal organ and postnotal organ of male, lateral view; (D) abdominal segments V – IX of male, lateral view (from Ma et al. 2014); (E) tergum VI of male, dorsal view, showing the anal horn; (F) and (G) genital bulbs, ventral and dorsal views; (H) aedeagus, ventral view; (I) left paramere, ventral view. Abbreviations: Ae, aedeagus; AH, anal horn; BP, basal process; DV, dorsal valve; Ep, epandrium; Gcx, gonocoxite; Gs, gonostylus; Hv, hypovalve; LP, lateral process; MT, median tooth; NO, notal organ; Pm, paramere; PnO, postnotal organ; VV, ventral valve. Scale bars: C, F, G = 0.20 mm, D = 1.00 mm, E = 0.50 mm, H, I = 0.10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/262940/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
A, B), unlike the roof-like wings of 
<emphasis box="[151,335,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">Furcatopanorpa</emphasis>
(Ma &amp; Hua 2011) and a few species of 
<taxonomicName box="[776,874,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[776,874,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">Panorpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The epedaphic larvae of 
<taxonomicName authority="Cheng, 1949" authorityName="Cheng" authorityYear="1949" box="[1162,1436,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Cerapanorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obtusa">
<emphasis box="[1162,1269,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">C. obtusa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cheng" box="[1283,1428,260,285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" refString="Cheng, F. Y. (1949) New species of Mecoptera from northwest China. Psyche, 56, 139 - 173. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1155 / 1949 / 36572" type="journal article" year="1949">Cheng, 1949</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
inhabit the surface of the ground, and bear long setae on both the head and the body (
<bibRefCitation author="Jiang" box="[1104,1315,295,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" refString="Jiang, L. &amp; Hua, B. Z. (2015) Morphological comparison of the larvae of Panorpa obtusa Cheng and Neopanorpa lui Chou &amp; Ran (Mecoptera: Panorpidae). Zoologischer Anzeiger, 255, 62 - 70. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. jcz. 2015.02.004" type="journal article" year="2015">Jiang &amp; Hua 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">
It should be noted that 
<taxonomicName authority="Carpenter, 1938" authorityName="Carpenter" authorityYear="1938" box="[466,808,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipennis">
<emphasis box="[466,618,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">P. flavipennis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Carpenter" box="[627,808,332,356]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" refString="Carpenter, F. M. (1938) Mecoptera from China, with descriptions of new species. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 40, 267 - 281." type="journal article" year="1938">Carpenter, 1938</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is not included in the new genus, although the species was regarded as belonging to the 
<taxonomicName box="[533,659,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="centralis">
<emphasis box="[533,659,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">P. centralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group previously by 
<bibRefCitation author="Carpenter" box="[904,1097,368,392]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" refString="Carpenter, F. M. (1938) Mecoptera from China, with descriptions of new species. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 40, 267 - 281." type="journal article" year="1938">Carpenter (1938)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Cheng" box="[1154,1313,367,392]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" refString="Cheng, F. Y. (1957) Revision of the Chinese Mecoptera. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 116, 1 - 118." type="journal article" year="1957">Cheng (1957)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Carpenter" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" refString="Carpenter, F. M. (1938) Mecoptera from China, with descriptions of new species. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 40, 267 - 281." type="journal article" year="1938">Carpenter (1938)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned that the species “possesses a single anal horn on 6th abdominal segment” in the original description, and clearly assigned the species to the 
<taxonomicName box="[725,823,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="centralis">
<emphasis box="[725,823,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">centralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. In a revision of the Chinese 
<taxonomicName authority="Cheng (1957)" authorityName="Cheng" authorityYear="1957" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">
Mecoptera, 
<bibRefCitation author="Cheng" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" refString="Cheng, F. Y. (1957) Revision of the Chinese Mecoptera. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 116, 1 - 118." type="journal article" year="1957">Cheng (1957)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
specifically described the “single anal horn on 6th abdominal segment very short”, and presented an illustration of the so-called anal horn (
<bibRefCitation author="Cheng" box="[586,817,511,536]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" refString="Cheng, F. Y. (1957) Revision of the Chinese Mecoptera. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 116, 1 - 118." type="journal article" year="1957">Cheng 1957: fig. 13</bibRefCitation>
), which is in fact only a very short lobe and definitely not the anal horn as we treat in this paper. Ironically, both 
<bibRefCitation author="Carpenter" box="[808,1001,548,572]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" refString="Carpenter, F. M. (1938) Mecoptera from China, with descriptions of new species. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 40, 267 - 281." type="journal article" year="1938">Carpenter (1938)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Cheng" box="[1056,1211,548,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" refString="Cheng, F. Y. (1957) Revision of the Chinese Mecoptera. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 116, 1 - 118." type="journal article" year="1957">Cheng (1957)</bibRefCitation>
noted that the wing membrane of 
<taxonomicName box="[305,455,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipennis">
<emphasis box="[305,455,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">P. flavipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is deep yellow, markedly different from the colorless or lacteous wing membrane of the new genus. More importantly, the male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[725,875,620,644]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Panorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipennis">
<emphasis box="[725,875,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">P. flavipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ from those of 
<taxonomicName box="[1106,1257,620,643]" class="Insecta" family="Panorpidae" genus="Cerapanorpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1106,1257,620,643]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">Cerapanorpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1263,1367,620,645]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1263,1367,620,645]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in the more slender hypovalves and the possession of distinct lobes on the gonostylus. In addition, the female genital plate (
<bibRefCitation author="Carpenter" box="[220,484,692,717]" pageId="4" pageNumber="97" refString="Carpenter, F. M. (1938) Mecoptera from China, with descriptions of new species. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 40, 267 - 281." type="journal article" year="1938">Carpenter 1938: fig. 12</bibRefCitation>
) is considerably different from that of the new genus in gross morphology.
</paragraph>
